		<header>
			
			<h1>SADC*: Agricultural trade policy debates and developments</h1>

						<div class="pdf-file">
				<a href="/en/layout/set/print/content/download/12120/496278/file/ddd5408a7c82a8b74b2d25addfb69acb.pdf">Download <img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pdf.gif" alt="" /></a>
			</div>
			
			<h4>
									</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p><b>*</b>This executive brief deals with agricultural trade policy debates and developments involving the seven SADC countries which are members of the SADC–European Union Economic Partnership Agreement configuration, undertaking trade negotiations with the EU.</p><p><b>About this update</b></p><p>This brief was updated in July 2011. The original executive brief was published in October 2008 and is available on request from agritrade-mail@cta.int</p><p>Other publications in this series and additional resources on ACP—EU agriculture and fisheries trade issues can be found online at http://agritrade.cta.int/</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<a name="eztoc496268_1" id="eztoc496268_1"></a><h2><b>1. Introduction and overview </b></h2><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>1.1 Agricultural production</b></p><p>Food and agricultural production in the countries of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) EU Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA) configuration is dominated by South Africa. South Africa is the major producer of maize, wheat, sorghum, millet, beef, poultry, dairy, sugar, and horticultural products, and has the potential to grow virtually all its basic foodstuffs and service a highly developed food processing sector. Indeed, while agriculture in South Africa accounts for 4.5% of GDP, agriculture and food processing combined account for 15% of GDP. Agricultural production in fellow SADC configuration countries and policy debates takes place in the shadow of this South African dominance. Neighbouring countries have however found important niches for their own agricultural production.</p><p>In Swaziland, sugar dominates, accounting for 60% of agricultural production, on the basis of sales to Southern African Customs Union (SACU) and EU markets. Cereals production in Swaziland has declined over time until only 40% of domestic requirements are met. Livestock, dairy and horticulture production all take place in the shadow of South Africa and are to varying degrees subjected to regulated trade.</p><p>A similar situation prevails in Botswana, where beef production dominates. Here 90% of commercialised beef production is exported to the EU. Botswana uses a variety of trade tools to regulate imports of maize, wheat, sorghum, pulses, poultry, beef, fresh milk, oranges, watermelons and vegetables, with a view to sustaining some level of local production. This includes the use of infant industry protection provisions. Botswana is however a net importer of staple food commodities.</p><p>Lesotho is in a similar position and through the use of import regulations seeks to maintain some production of maize, wheat, sorghum, beans and peas and higher value crops such as soya beans, potatoes, fruits, sunflowers, asparagus, garlic, paprika and other vegetables.</p><p>This regulation of imports in a context of a significant import dependence is also a characteristic of the Namibian agricultural sector: over half of all cereals consumed in Namibia are imported. Here agricultural trade policy tools are actively used to sustain and promote commercial production of maize, wheat and horticultural products, as well as millet and sorghum. As in Botswana, livestock dominates the Namibian agricultural economy.</p><p>Angola and Mozambique have enormous agricultural potential, which has been suppressed by decades of civil war. Formerly Angola was a major producer of coffee, sisal and bananas, with a potential for self-sufficiency in virtually all areas except wheat. However, currently only around 3% of arable land is under production. Efforts are under way to relaunch agricultural sector development.</p><p>Foreign investment is playing an important role in this process, particularly in the sugar and banana sectors in Mozambique, but also in the dairy sector. This is generating concern over land rights issues. In Mozambique and Angola, as across the whole of the SADC EPA region, agricultural production is divided between large-scale commercial production and small-scale/subsistence farming. This constitutes a major challenge to agriculture and agricultural trade policy development at the national level.</p><p><b>Table 1: Main agricultural commodities produced in SADC EPA configuration countries</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="443" valign="top">  <b>South Africa</b>
