</table>
<p>Source: WTO</p><p><b>1.2 Agricultural trade</b></p><p>Regional markets are of considerable importance to South Africa’s exports of food and agricultural products (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Divergent-trends-within-South-Africa-s-cereals-sector" target="_self">Divergent trends within South Africa’s cereals sector</a>’, May 2011). South Africa is also an important point of entry to the region for imported food and agricultural products. In some sectors the South African market is of considerable importance to SADC EPA configuration producers (e.g. for Swazi sugar and Namibian beef), or is a principal market targeted by new investments (e.g. in Mozambique). Apart from South Africa, only Swaziland is a net agricultural exporter.</p><p>In the last decade in certain major agricultural sectors such as sugar (but also bananas and horticulture), South African companies have concentrated new production investment in neighbouring countries which enjoy preferential access to overseas markets, with trade preferences playing a major role in these investment decisions.</p><p>While within SACU the principle of free movement of goods behind a common external tariff remains, in practice a multiplicity of trade policy tools is used to regulate trade. This needs to be seen in the context of the overwhelming dominance of the South African food and agricultural sector and the existence of a highly concentrated and advanced retail sector.</p><p>At the SADC level (which reaches beyond the membership of the SADC EPA configuration), while the SACU had granted duty-free quota-free access to its neighbours, this access is qualified and restricted by specific transitional arrangements (for sugar), onerous rules of origin (although these are being relaxed) and the strict application of sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) and food safety standards.</p><p><b>1.3 Situating agricultural trade policy</b></p><p>Agriculture and agricultural trade policy remain a national responsibility. However efforts are under way to coordinate national policies at regional level. This pooling of sovereignty is most advanced within the SACU, which involves five of the seven SADC EPA configuration countries. However the process of regional trade policy formulation takes place at many different levels, including the 15-member Southern African Development Community (SADC), and the 19-member Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).</p><p>Both SADC and COMESA are setting in place free-trade area (FTA) arrangements, and both have aspirations to establish customs unions. In addition one other SADC member, Tanzania, is already part of a customs union, the East African Community (EAC) Customs Union, which involves four other COMESA member states (Kenya, Uganda, Burundi and Rwanda). Thus, coordinating agricultural trade policy at a regional level is complicated by the multiple membership of governments in these overlapping regional trade bodies. Efforts are under way to harmonise these regional trade arrangements through the establishment of a ‘grand free-trade area’, encompassing the membership of the SACU, EAC, COMESA and SADC.</p><p>Beyond these overlapping regional groupings there is also the New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD)-based Comprehensive African Agricultural Development Programme (CAADP). The CAADP seeks to increase government expenditures on agriculture to 10% of their total budgets in order to attain annual agricultural sector growth of 6%. The CAADP provides the main framework for the extension of external assistance to agricultural development in Africa. In 2010 Swaziland and Mozambique made commitments under a CAADP compact.</p><a name="eztoc496268_2" id="eztoc496268_2"></a><h2><b>2. Regional agricultural trade policy developments</b></h2><p><b>2.1 Agriculture in the national context</b></p><p>SADC EPA configuration governments have different perspectives on the role of trade policy in national agricultural sector development. While coordination efforts are taking place, these initiatives are still in the early stages of elaboration, apart from in specific technical areas (such as SPS regulations and animal disease control measures). As a consequence their operational impact on national agricultural policy design and implementation is limited.</p><p>This leads to discrepancies between the application of agricultural trade policy tools at the national level and the nominal regional trade policy commitments. Reconciling these anomalies represents a major policy challenge and is a principal focus of ongoing regional trade negotiations.</p><p>The importance of the food and agricultural sector varies considerably across SADC EPA configuration economies. Generally, however, agriculture makes a far greater contribution to employment creation than it does to GDP and merchandise exports. Indeed, livelihood concerns can come to dominate policy formulation.</p><p><b>Table 2: Agricultural profile of full ACP members of the SADC EPA configuration</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
