<p>Source: Compiled by the author from FAO <i>C</i><i>ountry Briefs</i></p><p>Note: regarding population figures, there is an inconsistency between national figures and FAO data, with the suggestion being that FAO data may be seeing the agricultural labour force as a residual category (i.e. including rural pensioners).</p><p>Trends in the agricultural sector also vary considerably. In Namibia, the annual rate of growth in the agricultural sector has been increasing over the 2004–08 period (5% growth compared to 0.02% for the 1999–2003 period), with agricultural development programmes beginning to transform the national supply situation in key sectors (such as horticulture). In contrast, in Botswana, according to the WTO Secretariat, despite high levels of public assistance, there has been little improvement in production and domestic food security, with government programmes generally following a welfare &nbsp;rather than business-oriented approach. In Swaziland, despite efforts to promote diversification, the sugar sector continues to dominate. In Mozambique foreign investment is playing a major role in agriculture development (e.g. in sugar and bananas), while in Angola, efforts to promote foreign agricultural investment have proved less successful.</p><p>Nominally government perspectives on agricultural sector development are similar. The governments of Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland, Mozambique, Namibia and South Africa all place importance on food security as a policy objective, and agriculture is seen as playing a vital role in the social and economic fabric of all these countries. However there is considerable variation in how food security objectives are defined and how governments perceive the future trajectory for agricultural sector development. More importantly from a policy perspective, there is considerable variation in:</p>
<ul>

<li>the policy tools which governments use to promote agricultural sector development; </li>

<li>the relationship between agricultural policy and industrial policy (this is particularly relevant to the use of infant industry protection measures).</li>

<li>the extent to which each regulates the operation of market forces; </li>

<li>… and ultimately the success being achieved through the deployment of these policy tools.</li>

</ul>
<p><b>2.2 Agriculture and agricultural trade policy in the SACU</b></p><p>SACU is nominally a single market with free movement of goods and a common external tariff (CET). However Article 18.1 of the SACU Agreement allows exceptions to the principle of free movement of goods related to infant industry protection (Article 26) and special arrangements for agricultural products (Article 29). There are differences in how governments feel the principle of free movement of goods should be applied in the food and agricultural sector.</p><p>The Namibian government favours a managed approach towards ‘a fully liberalised agricultural trade regime’, implying a continued use of quantitative restrictions and licensing for ‘controlled products’ under any coordinated SACU agricultural policy. This pragmatic approach is seen as increasingly relevant given the price volatility on cereals markets (see <i>Agritrade</i> articles ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Prospects-for-global-cereals-markets-to-2019" target="_self">Prospects for global cereals markets to 2019’ and ‘Food prices reach 200...</a>’, February 2011).</p><p>Similar systems operate in other SACU countries. In Swaziland dairy markets are regulated using import quota restrictions, while Botswana uses similar measures in both its dairy and poultry sectors. The government of Lesotho similarly favours a case-by-case approach to liberalisation in the agriculture sector. Government statements however do not always reflect these similarities.</p><p>Differences in approach in part reflect the varied financial capacities of governments to use financial support instruments. Given its mineral wealth Botswana makes greater use of financial support instruments. In Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland, there is substantially less scope for the use of such tools. As a consequence greater use is made of import licensing arrangements and seasonal import restrictions to regulate supply to local markets. These trade tools however are used with varying degrees of sophistication and varying degrees of success. Namibia has successfully used trade tools as part of wider programmes to substantially expand horticultural production for domestic markets.</p><p>Revenue shocks associated with the global economic downturn however have led to a renewed interest in the use of non-financial policy tools to support agricultural development. This trend can also be seen in the EU where a debate on strengthening the functioning of food supply chains has been launched.</p><p>Food and agricultural products enjoy higher average tariff protection than non-food and agricultural products. In recent years average tariff protection has shifted ‘in favour of agricultural products’ (up from 9.6% in 2002 to 10.1% in 2009). A number of food and agricultural products are also subject to mixed duties (both <i>ad valorem</i> and fixed duties), which provide higher levels of effective protection for these products. This reflects efforts to actively use trade policy to support the structural development of the food and agricultural sector within the SACU.</p><p>Certain anomalies in the application of the CET have arisen as a result of the bilateral EU–South Africa Trade Development and Cooperation Agreement (TDCA), with efforts under way to resolve these through the ongoing SADC–EU EPA negotiations.</p><p>Across a number of SADC EPA configuration countries, land rights and land issues remain contentious. Within the SACU these are largely linked to long-standing efforts to promote land reform in post-apartheid South Africa and Namibia. Beyond the SACU the issue of land acquisition by foreign companies is a policy issue of growing significance.</p><p>At the level of regional agricultural policy formulation, Article 39 of the 2002 SACU Agreement calls on member states to ‘agree to co-operate on agricultural policies in order to ensure the co-ordinated development of the agricultural sector’. This falls far short of a commitment to the establishment of a SACU common agricultural policy. However even with these more limited ambitions the WTO Secretariat has noted ‘little progress’ in coordinating and cooperating on agricultural policies, with work ‘still at an early stage’.</p><p>At the aggregate level it needs to be borne in mind that the SACU is a net importer of staple foods, with import dependency steadily increasing. For example, while South Africa was once self-sufficient in wheat, imports now account for approximately 40% of domestic needs. While SACU remains a surplus producer of maize, it is unclear how long this situation will continue.</p><p><b>2.3 Agriculture and agricultural trade policy in the SADC</b></p><p>While functional cooperation in the agricultural sector has been part of the SADC programme since 1980, and efforts to harmonise policy date back to the 1990s, substantive work on establishing the national baseline for the development of a regional agricultural policy began in March 2008. A synthesis report on key agricultural policy issues was drafted and subjected to technical discussions in April 2010. Here the importance of having a formal, legally binding common agricultural policy was agreed. Technical work is now underway to clearly articulate:</p>
<ul>

<li>the policy visions, goals and principles of such a policy;</li>

<li>the policy interventions to be permitted and the conditions for their use;</li>

<li>the implementation arrangements for the management of the regional agricultural policy.</li>

</ul>
<p>A regional agricultural policy document is expected to emerge in 2012, with political approval being secured at key ‘milestones’ in parallel with this technical work. This provides background to the regional agricultural policy process against which The intra-regional agricultural trade negotiations need to be seen against this background to the regional agricultural policy process (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/ACP-regional-trade/Moving-forward-SADC-s-regional-agricultural-policy" target="_self">Moving forward SADC’s regional agricultural policy</a>’, July 2011).</p><p>While Mozambique has been part of the SADC Trade Protocol process since 1996, initial problems were faced in implementing tariff reduction commitments. However Mozambique has subsequently honoured in full its tariff phase-down commitments. In contrast, Angola only acceded to the SADC Trade Protocol in March 2003 and has not yet submitted a tariff phase-down schedule to the SADC Secretariat.</p><p>SADC commitments on the elimination of non-tariff barriers to trade are also tempered by a recognition that some existing agricultural trade policy tools can play an important role in attaining wider development policy objectives. Against this background a pragmatic approach has been adopted in the SADC Trade Negotiations Forum.</p><p>Under the SADC Trade Protocol a distinction was made between elimination of non-tariff barriers such as import quotas, customs procedures and export subsidies, where commitments were sought, and such non-tariff measures as local content requirements, levies and other border charges, and import &nbsp;and export licensing arrangements, which were excluded from the process of removal of non-tariff barriers, providing that such measures were minimally trade distorting.</p><p>At the SADC level it is recognised that a careful assessment needs to be made before taking decisions on individual non-tariff measures. In the case of Mozambique these general SADC-level trade policy commitments need to be reconciled with an agricultural trade policy which:</p><p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; maintains high average tariffs on basic food products (12% for agricultural products compared to an average of 10.1%);</p><p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; maintains very high levels of tariff protection for certain products in order to promote investment (e.g. sugar);</p><p>c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; establishes minimum prices for sugar, cashew nuts, tobacco and cotton (while allowing the free play of market forces in other products);</p><p>d)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; uses export licences to promote national ownership of export activities in the cashew nut export sector;</p><p>e)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; uses single channel marketing arrangements for both the domestic distribution and export of certain agricultural commodities (e.g. sugar).</p><p>In the case of Angola, while the government has been undertaking considerable liberalisation in recent years, there are still some peak tariffs for food and agricultural products, while special import regimes are in place for certain products, including import bans and import licensing arrangements. With bound rates of 55% for most agricultural tariff lines, considerable scope exists for increasing applied tariffs in Angola. In addition the government of Angola continues to maintain a number of state enterprises in the food and agricultural sector, although since 2005 these have been subject to a degree of privatisation. Overall, Angola is only beginning to offer trade preferences to its SADC partners, with most favoured nation (MFN) duties largely still being applied.</p><p><b>2.4 Recent developments at the SADC, COMESA and wider levels</b></p><p>The SADC has had an ambitious agenda for trade and economic integration, involving the establishment of a FTA by 2008, a Customs Union by 2010, a common market by 2015, a monetary union by 2016 and a single currency by 2018. However, the approach to tariff harmonisation proposed would have required significant changes to the SACU common external tariff. As a consequence, at the 30<sup>th</sup> anniversary celebrations of the formation of the SADC, the launch of a SADC customs union was postponed, due to the extensive work still required to harmonise policies, regulatory frameworks and standards.</p><p>The regional agricultural trade situation is further complicated by Swaziland’s membership of the COMESA process. Initial plans for a COMESA customs union by 2008 were postponed following a commitment in 2008 by the heads of state to the establishment of a ‘grand FTA’. As a consequence of this wider development, only a minority of COMESA members signed up to membership of the COMESA customs union launched in Victoria Falls in June 2009. At the official opening of the 29<sup>th</sup> meeting of the COMESA Council of Ministers in December 2010, the beginning of 2012 was established as the new date for the establishment of a COMESA CET.</p><p>Moving over to a common external tariff in food and agricultural products is likely to prove particularly problematic, given the differing levels of protection of individual food and agricultural products across COMESA member states and the extensive use made by some COMESA members of special dispensations. These range from the exceptions granted to Kenya to maintain tariff protection for sugar until February 2012, and the blanket exceptions granted to Swaziland not to implement tariff reductions, given its membership of the SACU.</p><p>Against this background, it is unclear to what extent the focus of wider regional trade integration efforts is shifting towards a pragmatic application of existing free-trade area commitments, rather than the deepening of the trade integration process (via the creation of customs unions). The establishment of a multiplicity of bilateral ‘simplified trade regime initiatives’ designed to address practical obstacles in the way of bilateral trade is indicative of a more pragmatic approach.</p><p>The proposed tripartite FTA (T-FTA) offers no easy solutions to these problems. Analysts have pointed out that if the new regional trade deal is to deliver real benefits, it will have to address a range of non-tariff barriers to trade, particularly in the agricultural sector. Yet SACU governments favour a pragmatic approach which recognises the role that certain trade policy tools can play in stimulating national agricultural development in the context of the market realities faced in the Southern and Eastern African region. SACU ministers have insisted that the T-FTA process has to be member state driven, with texts prepared by the regional secretariats being seen as inputs to the process, but not as the starting point for negotiations. This means a substantial process of negotiations will be needed if the T-FTA process is to progress. In addition, if the T-FTA process is to be member state driven, then it is essential that clear and coherent domestic agricultural and agro-industrial policies are in place at the national level. These can then be harmonised at the regional level. In the absence of clear national policies, obstacles to expanding regional agricultural trade are likely to remain in place despite the nominal trade liberalisation commitments made (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/EPAs/SADC-EU-EPA-negotiations-on-hold-as-grand-FTA-challenges-become-apparent" target="_self">SADC–EU EPA negotiations on hold as “grand FTA” challenges become apparent</a>’, July 2011).</p><a name="eztoc496268_3" id="eztoc496268_3"></a><h2><b>3. Wider trade negotiations and developments</b></h2><p><b>3.1 The EPA negotiations</b></p><p>While EPA tariff issues are largely addressed under the TDCA, ‘Everything But Arms’ initiative (EBA) and the EU’s (interim) EPA – (I)EPA – commitments, there remain a number of agriculture-related issues outstanding in the EPA negotiations. The first relates to the possible loss of duty-free access to the EU market (which was most severely felt by Namibia), if eligibility for duty-free access under the EU’s December 2007 transitional regulation were to be withdrawn. During 2010 the danger of withdrawal of duty-free access receded, with a renewed focus on the substantive issues to be addressed. This lifted the shadow that had been hanging over the Namibian beef sector.</p><p>The second outstanding issue relates to the right to continue to use a variety of traditional trade policy tools (import licences, infant industry protection, export licences and export taxes). There is a variety of provisions in the interim EPA which are inconsistent with the current agricultural trade practice within the SACU, with a number of governments seeking the removal or modification of these provisions prior to signature. In 2010, support within the SADC EPA group was consolidated around these issues behind the consensus reached with the EU in Swakopmund in March 2009.</p><p>The third issue relates to improvements in South Africa’s access to EU food and agricultural markets. By the time the TDCA is fully implemented in 2012, South Africa will retain protection on just 108 agricultural product lines, while the EU will enjoy protection on 615 lines. Correcting this imbalance has been a consistent objective of the South African government, with improved market access for wine, sugar and canned fruit being sought. There is a new optimism that an agreement can be reached.</p><p>The fourth issue relates to closer cooperation around SPS issues. Analysis suggests that the full potential of an EPA agreement in this area is not being exploited. A call for the establishment of special technical committees ‘to deal with TBT and SPS barriers to trade’, backed up by ‘specific development cooperation commitments and mechanisms for their implementation’ has been made (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/content/view/full/5246" target="_self">Review of the treatment of NTB issues under (I)EPAs posted</a>’, October 2010). The relevance of such arrangements, if operationally effective, is highlighted by the recent discovery of banned veterinary medicine residues in Namibian cattle slaughtered for consumption in the EU (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Beef/Need-for-intensified-dialogue-of-evolving-food-safety-policy-highlighted" target="_self">Need for intensified dialogue on evolving food safety policy highlighted</a>’, Month 2011). Intensifying collaboration on SPS compliance could potentially help reduce both the additional costs of SPS compliance and the threat of trade disruptions. Close cooperation on traceability schemes already appears to have resulted in considerable progress in the area of trade disruptions.</p><p><b>3.2 Other trade negotiations</b></p><p>Despite having a CET, SACU member states maintain a range of bilateral trade deals. For BLNS countries (the grouping of Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland), this largely involves regional partners and non-reciprocal trade agreements with OECD countries. While there is a logical need to rationalise these bilateral deals, the considerable administrative effort required to reconcile inconsistencies means that unless sectors are particularly sensitive, or major trade volumes are involved (e.g. with the EU), then a pragmatic approach is adopted. Individual governments are also involved in various cooperation agreements that do not involve any tariff commitments.</p><p>The SACU has concluded, or is negotiating, a range of preferential trade agreements, most notably the SACU–Mercosur, SACU–India and SACU–China trade arrangements. These agreements are not as ambitious as FTA agreements, as they involve tariff reductions rather than tariff elimination, and have a more limited product coverage, allowing the exclusion of a wider range of sensitive products.</p><p>The SACU has made extensive tariff elimination commitments in the context of the SADC Trade Protocol and associated SADC FTA. This however involves special treatment for sensitive products (mainly sugar and sugar-containing products), where liberalisation will not take place until 2012, and also involves application of strict rules of origin to prevent the routing of cheap third-country products to SACU markets via SADC countries.</p><p>Beyond the SADC region, in addition to the ongoing EPA negotiations, the SACU has concluded an FTA agreement with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) and was engaged in FTA negotiations with the EAC and the US, but these have been respectively placed on hold (in the light of the grand FTA discussions in the region) and downgraded to a more narrowly defined Trade and Investment Cooperation Agreement. Negotiations are also ongoing with India.</p><p><b>Table 3: The network of bilateral trade agreements in SACU</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
