<p>&nbsp;Source: TRALAC</p><a name="eztoc496268_4" id="eztoc496268_4"></a><h2><b>4. Current agricultural trade policy debates and issues</b></h2><p><b>4.1 Establishing a consensus on agricultural policy</b></p><p>In the SACU and wider SADC EPA configuration, there are divergent views on regional agriculture and agricultural trade policy issues. Some implicitly argue for a gradual pragmatic approach, with common policies being allowed to emerge from the process of coordination and cooperation. Others argue for the development of regional policies that should take precedence over national policies.</p><p>Those who favour giving primacy to regional policies take the view that non-tariff barriers to trade should simply be swept away. Those who favour a gradual approach believe that seasonal quantitative restrictions on ‘controlled products’ designated sensitive, and the use of import licences in other ‘controlled product’ sectors, are an essential part of national food security policy and agricultural development policy, and should therefore be tolerated within regional integration processes.</p><p>It is acknowledged that any changes to the approach to non-tariff barriers to trade (notably seasonal restrictions and import licences) would be likely to lead to very different production and employment patterns to those currently prevailing in the sectors subjected to such measures. Given this reality, any consensus on regional agriculture and agricultural trade policy needs to be built from the bottom up. If the depth and quality of the dialogue between member state ministries and agricultural sector stakeholders can be improved, and if effective networks of communication among national governments, stakeholders and regional bodies can be set in place, then member states may be more willing to allocate a coordinating role to regional institutions. Such a coordinating role could ultimately give rise to a common regional agricultural policy.</p><p>Without effective mechanisms for building regional policy on the basis of national realities, governments will continue to be reluctant to pool sovereignty, with regional policy formulation remaining firmly subordinated to diverse national policy making processes.</p><p><b>4.2 The future role of trade policy and financial support instruments</b></p><p>A critical debate revolves around the future use of financial support instruments, as opposed to trade policy tools. Debates on the use of trade policy tools cannot be divorced from South Africa’s economic dominance. This is why the right to use trade policy tools is enshrined in the SACU Agreement and accommodated in the SADC Trade Protocol process.</p><p>In addition, debates on the use of trade policy tools are commonly merged with the wider debate on the elimination of non-policy-related barriers to trade (e.g. inadequate transport, storage and preservation infrastructure, unofficial taxes and levies, inefficient customs procedures and differing product standards). While the elimination of non-policy-related barriers to trade needs to be accorded priority, since this is often a difficult task, attention can shift to the removal of policy-based obstacles to trade. In the SACU this is compounded by the virtual elimination of non-policy-related barriers, with the focus therefore inevitably falling on the use of trade policy tools.</p><p>These debates need to be clearly differentiated and addressed separately, taking into account wider regional realities. Given the recognition of the continued relevance of certain trade policy tools, the major issue would appear to be ensuring full transparency in the application of these trade policy tools, and full assessments of their economic costs and benefits.</p><p>Attempts are under way in the region to explore more coordinated approaches to the use of agricultural trade policy tools, in order to minimise disruptions of intra-regional trade. This includes an exploration of possible policy measures to improve the functioning of markets in view of the considerable concentration of economic power within supply chains, which undermines the functioning of free markets.</p><p>Proposals for the establishment of regional financing facilities to support agricultural development are also being developed. By addressing some of the underlying problems of competitiveness and unequal development in the southern African region, this could reduce the need to use certain agricultural trade policy tools. However, since these discussions in the SACU are linked to the future SACU revenue-sharing arrangement, early progress is not anticipated.</p><p>This provides essential background to EPA-related discussions on the removal of quantitative restrictions on trade, the dismantling of infant industry protection regimes, and the future of agricultural safeguard provisions.</p><p><b>4.3 The future basis of regional trade integration</b></p><p>The essential dichotomy in the region is between those who wish to focus on effectively making existing commitments operational in a pragmatic fashion, based on the current primacy of national policy making processes, and those who wish to push ahead with commitments to deepen economic cooperation and integration. This division can be found at both the SACU and SADC levels.</p><p>The ‘pragmatists’ seek to deploy the region’s human and institutional resources on consolidating existing arrangements and addressing fundamental structural constraints. The ‘regionalists’, in contrast, argue that by abandoning existing commitments to the creation of a SADC customs union, then momentum will be lost and regional integration will become mired in day-to-day disputes. In this context it should be noted that regional policy analysts have argued that ‘most of the economic gains from lower tariffs and improved trade facilitation do not depend on the creation of a customs union and could be gained from a thorough implementation of the current Trade Protocol and upcoming Free-Trade Area’.</p><p>Following the 2007/08 food crisis the ‘pragmatist’ approach appears to be gaining ground at both the SACU and SADC levels. However to avoid becoming mired in day-to-day disputes it is essential that stakeholders can be routinely and transparently incorporated into national and regional policy formulation processes. This will require considerable investment in building policies from the bottom up.</p><p><b>4.4 SPS issues</b></p><p>SPS-related issues are dealt with under Article 16 of the SADC Trade Protocol, and Articles 30 and 18 of the 2002 SACU Treaty. Generally trade in the SADC region proceeds smoothly, largely unimpeded by SPS disputes. Where there have been outbreaks of disease, or even suspicions of pending outbreaks, borders have been closed, but only until the issue has been resolved – although there have been instances where a lack of collaboration has led to extensive application of SPS-related trade restrictions (e.g. concerns over fruit fly infestation resulted in bans on Namibian watermelons for three years on SPS grounds). There is therefore a need to strengthen collaboration on SPS issues, both bilaterally and through regional bodies. However, this will require human resource constraints to be addressed across the region (for example, in Namibia 60% of posts for technical staff in the governmental veterinary department remain unfilled). It will also require increased investment in technical infrastructure (e.g. accredited laboratories and scientific research bodies).</p><p>There is a recognised need to strengthen interaction with private sector stakeholders in the policy formulation process. The absence of effective engagement with producers’ associations and private sector bodies can complicate problems in enforcing SPS standards, particularly for production serving local markets.</p><p>There have been efforts to assist SADC governments in engaging with the activities of international standards setting bodies. However participation on a regional level has not been coordinated, despite a commitment to adopting a collective approach, in order to meaningfully influence international standards. Finally, there is a vital need to harmonise the various national legislation in the region with relevant international standards, in order to improve access to more favourably priced markets.</p><p><b>4.5 Rules of Origin issues</b></p><p>While the SADC Rules of Origin (RoO) were originally designed on the basis of an across-the-board percentage value and a ‘Change in Tariff Heading’ (CTH) requirement, which largely mirrored the COMESA and EAC rules, these were never fully implemented. A product-specific approach was adopted in the amended SADC Trade Protocol. This uses a line-by-line approach for RoO.</p><p>Goods must either be wholly produced in a SADC member state to be considered a local product and qualify for preferences or, where imported materials are used, must be transformed mostly based on a technical test. Many goods are also subject to CTH requirements, and for some products a percentage-based rule is used, mostly by setting a maximum threshold for imported materials. In many cases two or three tests are used jointly, for example the CTH test in combination with a maximum threshold for imported material.</p><p>For a number of products, no SADC preference exists and thus no RoO (e.g. wheat flour and certain wheat flour products). The negotiations on wheat RoOs have been continuing for years, with no resolution. Since the region is a net importer of wheat, most members are proposing to have ‘Single Stage Transformation’ (i.e. the wheat can be sourced anywhere but processed in the member state into flour). SACU does not have its own rules, but is now in a process of finalising a Common Rules Certificate.</p><a name="eztoc496268_4_1" id="eztoc496268_4_1"></a><h3>Main sources</h3><p>1. WTO, ‘Trade policy review: Botswana, Lesotho, Namibia South Africa and Swaziland’, November 2009</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp322_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp322_e.htm</a></p><p>2. WTO, ‘Trade policy review: Mozambique’, April 2009</p><p>
